Title: b'Oblique Workout for Ripped Obliques (7 EXERCISES!!)'
Description:
b'Get ripped abs and shredded obliques (meal plan and workouts)
http://athleanx.com/x/complete-system-to-a-ripped-core

Oblique workouts and exercises are a critical and often overlooked element of building a ripped set of abs.  Even the sharpest six pack won\xe2\x80\x99t look perfect unless it is framed out by an equally shredded set of obliques.  Because of the orientation of the internal and external obliques, when they are developed and your body fat is low enough, they act to frame out the abs. 

In this video, I show you a 7 exercise oblique workout that will help to attack these important core muscles from every angle.  Each one of the moves is heavy on rotation, as this is a key component of all effective oblique exercises.  You\xe2\x80\x99ll have options that you can do standing, on the floor or hanging from a bar.

The oblique exercises in this workout include:

Cyclone Leg Raises
Oblique Twists
Reverse Corkscrews
Thread the Needle
1 Leg Plank Hop Twists
Floating Scissors
Hi-Lo Woodchoppers

Each of these oblique exercises targets the obliques in a slightly unique way.  With a heavy dose of rotation, you will be hitting the lateral core muscles from all angles and with all levels of difficulty.  The best way to attack this oblique workout is to perform each exercise with as little rest as possible between exercises.  Take just enough time to transition from one to the next and try to take each one to failure.  You should not be able to perform another rep with good form before moving onto the next exercise in the workout.

The obliques often get overlooked in favor of concentrating on the more popular rectus abdominus (the muscle responsible for the visual six pack abs).  This is understandable, but I\xe2\x80\x99m telling you it is a major mistake.  Even visible abs may appear thick and blocky if you don\xe2\x80\x99t have a game plan for getting those oblique muscles developed as well.

Meantime, none of this will matter if you can\xe2\x80\x99t get your nutrition and diet in check.  If you eat poorly you will likely never have a low enough body fat level to reveal your hard work spent developing your abs and obliques.  In order to get the muscles of your core to show you have to be dedicated enough to eat the right foods to keep that fat level down low enough to show them.

The ATHLEAN-X Training System available at http://athleanx.com includes both the ab and oblique workouts necessary to develop a sick six pack as well as the day by day meal plans to get low body fat.  You can get both in one system and start training like an athlete today.

For more oblique workout videos and advice on how to get a six pack fast, be sure to subscribe to our channel here on youtube at http://youtube.com/user/jdcav24'

La evidencia cient\xc3\xadfica nos confirma que la fuerza adquirida en cualquier ejercicio es espec\xc3\xadfica y depende de la angulaci\xc3\xb3n y tipo de movimiento que realicemos.

Esto quiere decir, que si trabajamos solamente los press parciales, desarrollaremos mucha fuerza en la parte final del recorrido, pero fallaremos en la parte inicial de este press.

A si mismo sucede con el trabajo isom\xc3\xa9trico (la fuerza que ejercemos es igual a la resistencia movida), ya que la evidencia nos confirma que el desarrollo de la fuerza est\xc3\xa1 directamente relacionado con el \xc3\xa1ngulo especifico en el que se ejerce esta fuerza.

Lo que quiere decir, que si trabajamos las paradas en un punto de estancamiento, estamos potenciando la fuerza espec\xc3\xadfica en ese punto, algo MUY beneficioso y que nos puede hacer subir muchos kilos en press banca o cualquier otro ejercicio.

Title: b'2013 British Championship goes to Field Marshal Montgomery'
Description:
b"The British Pipe Band Championships in 2013 were held in Bathgate on 25 May in Meadow Park. The organisers are to be congratulated on a great event. This was first and foremost a pipe band competition, and the focus throughout was on the bands - no noisy side shows or other distractions.

There seems to be a great respect for bands here, and bands of all types flourish. Three of the fifteen bands competing in the Grade One competition come from this area (Boghall, Shotts and Torpichen). There are also brass bands (including the world renowned Whitburn Band just up the road), flute bands (of all types), and accordion bands.

This lovely march, strathspey and reel performance gained Field Marshal Montgomery pipe band under the leadership of Richard Parkes, MBE, first place in the Grade One competition. A couple of shaky starts at the Worlds last year and personnel changes in the band over the winter perhaps made some wonder whether or not this band could maintain its exceptional, consistent high qualities. This was the answer.

Music played:

March: Balmoral Highlanders (Angus Mackay)
Strathspey: John Roy Stewart (traditional)
Reel: Charlie's Welcome (traditional)"

Title: b'Pilates Masters Kathy Grant & Ron Fletcher'
Description:
b'Pilates Masters Kathy Grant and Ron Fletcher share thoughts and memories of Joseph and Clara Pilates.

Go back in time -- more than half a century! -- to the days of "cold showers after every workout" when "that irascible old German," Joseph Pilates, and his wife and partner Clara, were first developing their revolutionary fitness and conditioning method. Back to a simpler, more innocent time when two young dancers -- Kathy Grant and Ron Fletcher -- 'sought the Pilates' therapeutic help for dance-related knee injuries and wound up becoming not only devoted long-term students but, ultimately, the most revered teachers of the Pilates method.

This delightful and charming conversation / reminiscence between Grant and Fletcher, both 84, took place October, 2005 at Kathy Grant's New York University studio and is a "first-ever" on film. See how these two Pilates Masters -- and great old friends -- have continued to learn and grow in their practice, development and preservation of the original genius articulated by Joseph and Clara Pilates.

Witty, intelligent and divinely personal. Full of the stories and anecdotes that bring Joseph and Clara Pilates to life! 

To Order go to www.fletcherpilates.com'

Title: b'Training in a gym without a partner - Rock climbing on the TRUBLUE Auto Belay'
Description:
b"Hi, I'm Chris Wall, head coach and trainer with the Boulder Rock Club
In this video, I'm going to show you some of the basics of training in the climbing gym.
I'm going to take you through some of the basic pieces of equipment you're going to find in most climbing gyms and show you how to most effectively use them so you can reach your personal climbing goals
Far and away one of the most useful tools in the climbing gym is the auto belay
In essence, an auto belay is a mechanism that provides an assisted top rope belay
So if you're coming in and you don't have a partner, you can still get as much climbing in as you need, you can do laps on routes, you can downclimb, or if you just got a little bit of time you can get a very intense workout done in a very short period of time
An auto belay basically take the place of a top rope belayer, so anything you can do on a top rope, you can do on an auto belay
So if you're working on your endurance, not only can you climb all the way up and be lowered down from the top just like with a top rope belayer, you can climb up and climb all the way back down, you can do laps, you can go up, down as much as you want
If you're climbing alone, or with friends, bouldering is a great training option
Remember to warm up gradually on easy boulder problems getting progressively harder as you go
And give yourself plenty of rest between boulder problems.
If you're bouldering alone, often times we forget to rest enough and we end up having to end our session early because we've totally blown ourselves out
So remember to take time to sit down and take it easy
Bouldering is a crucible of climbing technique and you can use it as a tool to work on moves that you find especially difficult
Go into the bouldering area and find the type of move that you know gives you trouble, whether it's bouldering or it's on routes or it's on traditional routes
If it's a crossthrough, set those up in the cave. If you have trouble with crimps and dead pointing from crimp to crimp, build that kind of problem
If pinches are your issue, make sure you select a lot of pinches on your boulder problems
Whatever it is, find routes that you can make challenging, but not impossible and then work them into submission
Another strategy you can utilize in the bouldering cave is traversing
And while you're traversing, consider moving up and down. This will increase the variety of options you have, and start using other muscles that aren't hit as hard when climbing in a traditional fashion which is typically straight up
Another really useful piece of training equipment is a campus board
Campus board is basically a slightly open overhanging board with different sized hand holds or rungs
Campusing means that you'll be pulling yourself up without the aid of your feet
Now this can be very stressful, especially for the novice so we've installed foot holds so people can do the same type of move while keeping their feet on as they build up enough strength to eventually take their feet off
Campusing helps you build finger strength and power as well as upper body strength and power
And this is essential for every type of climber, whether you're a boulderer, sport climber, or a traditional climber
So before you start training on the campus board, you want to make sure you warm up thoroughly
And you can do that on the climbing wall, in the bouldering cave, or on the campus board itself
When you start your training you want to be holding onto holds that you find manageable and doing moves that you can actually do and repeat on both sides of your body.
You're trying to do this training as symmetrically as possible
Make sure while you're campusing that you keep your hand open and you avoid moving into a crimped grip
This is to avoid finger injury
There's basically no end to the variety of patterns of movement that you can do on a campus board, but one of the most basic and a good place to start is moving one hand up and then matching the other hand beside it and then moving that hand up and matching again
Go up as far as you can on the board and when you start to get tired stop and come down, take a rest, and then repeat
Another slightly more difficult method of campusing is where you go hand over hand. This will force you to pull further and hit the board harder using more contact strength and building more power
A very advanced maneuver is the double clutch
Do not attempt this unless you have mastered moving your hands one over the other
With the double clutch you will be moving both hands at the same time to the next rung
This requires enormous power and fantastic timing
These are just a few ways to train in the gym to build your power, your endurance and your stamina
Whether you want to climb V10 or you want to climb a 10 pitch 5.8, these tools can help you reach your goals
For more information, check out AutoBelay.com. Thank you

Check out the amazing TRUBLUE Auto Belay at eldowalls.com/TRUBLUE-AutoBelays"

Title: b'How to Do Forward Lunges with Dumbbells'
Description:
b'Check out Bas Rutten's Liver Shot on MMA Surge: http://bit.ly/MMASurgeEp1
Muscles Worked

This exercise targets the muscles in your abs, hips and legs, including the transverse abdominus, obliques, gluteus maximus, quadriceps and hamstrings.\xc2\xa0

Getting Started

Start of by holding a dumbbell in each of your hands. Let your arms rest by your sides. Stand up straight and engage your core muscles.\xc2\xa0

For a lighter workout, you can do this exercise without using the dumbbells. Place your hands on your hips for balance.\xc2\xa0

Perform the Exercise

Once you're positioned with the dumbbells, you can start doing the lunges.\xc2\xa0

* Begin from a standing position with the dumbbells held at your sides.\xc2\xa0
* Step forward with your right foot and bend the right knee.\xc2\xa0
* Don't let the forward knee push past the toe below it. Instead, keep it in line with the ankle.\xc2\xa0
* Drop the weight of your body straight down.\xc2\xa0
* Keep your weight in line with your shoulders, and your shoulders in line with your hips.\xc2\xa0
* Extend your left leg behind you and push the left knee straight down to the floor.\xc2\xa0
* Then step back up with your right foot and return to the standing position.\xc2\xa0
* To control your breathing, try to inhale when you step forward with the front foot and then exhale as you push up to the starting position.\xc2\xa0
* Repeat this movement with the opposite leg and continue alternating for a full workout.\xc2\xa0

Muscle Focus: Abdominals.
Objective: Build abdominal strength and control. 

Start Position: Sit cross legged, bring your knees to your shoulders and hold the tops of both feet with your hands. Curl into a ball, gazing into your abdominals, and pulling the abdominals to the spine. 

Movement: Exhale and engage the powerhouse to roll onto your knees, keeping the spine in a C-curve, rolling forward until the top of the head comes to the Mat and the hips are directly over the knees. Inhale, maintaining the C-curve, roll back to balance on the shoulder blades, with hips over shoulders. Let go of your feet, switch the cross of the legs, and grasp back onto both feet. Exhale return to start position and repeat. 

Precautions: Avoid this exercise if you have had a neck or spine injury. It is recommended that you are proficient in performing Rolling Like a Ball and Seal prior to attempting this exercise. Maintain the C-curve shape of the spine and the lift and scoop of the abdominals.

135 lbs x 2
225 lbs x 2
315 lbs x 2
445 lbs x 1

Worksets

540 lbs x 2 (re-started reps) @9

Speed Sets

3 sets of 450 lb triples (continuous reps)

Reverse-Grip Pullups - Bodyweight (227.4 lbs right after the workout) + 5 lbs x 8 Reps

Goodmornings - 225 lbs x 8 Reps

This is the last week of the 4 exercise circuit (thank God)."

Title: b'Disused Shale Mine / Cave, Mid Calder, West Lothian'
Description: b"Disused Mine in Mid Calder. Quote from a website: These early shale workings supplied Oakbank Oil Works prior to sinking Oakbank No. 1 and 2 Pits. Substantial remains exist of workings in the cliffs on the west bank of the Linhouse Water that now form part of Almondell and Calderwood Country Park. The 1869 estate plan (below) suggests that the standard gauge mineral railway that subsequently served Oakbank No. 1 & 2 Pits initially terminated close to the east bank of the Linhouse water, from where a bridge across the river provided access to the mines in Calder Wood.\n\nEfforts were made during the 1990's to block access into these adits. Prior to that, the adventurous (or foolhardy) were able to explore a network of stoop and room workings extending back into the cliff. In some area, the presence of timber props protruding a foot or so from the floor of the tunnel suggested that the original roof had collapsed, leaving a void above the original workings. The mine entrances can only be reached following a difficult scramble down the steep sides of the valley, then following a rough track beside the river which is only safely accessible when water in the river is low."

Title: b'Weighted Bench Dips for Bigger Arms & Chest'
Description:
b"Yes, I admit this is an extreme example of me doing bench dips with heavy weight but guess how much bigger my arms and chest will be after using this dipping technique in my arm and chest workouts?

You will see most guys do the same bench dip exercise that I'm doing but their version is much more dangerous by stacking up tons of plates with a danger of the plates falling off and injuring them.

There is some discomfort in the way I do this exercise but it is much safer than stacking up pates on my lap

The major benefit you get from weighted bench dips is that it will pack on lots of muscle mass in your arms (your triceps or the back of your arms) and chest super-fast due to the fact you are getting stronger using much heavier weights and all you need to do is sets of 6-to-12 reps to get bigger arms and chest.

It may be easier and more convenient to do drop sets with plates stacked on your lap but it's much safer to do bench dips with drop sets for bigger arms and chest.

Try out regular dips if you are able to take full advantage of you using your full bodyweight instead of just half your bodyweight here like in bench dips but I'll understand if you have no dipping station available at your home or gym

If you want to take your chest and arm workout to the net level with bench dips then pause at the bottom of each rep for 2 seconds to make your arm and chest muscles do most of the work.

Title: b'Dmitry Klokov- CrossFit Tabata (Part 1)'
Description:
b'Dmitry Klokov demonstrates a weightlifting style of Tabata training while listening to TABATA SONGS. Using 8 exercises from his own strength training program, Klokov showcases his world-class strength as well as his stamina with this mind-blowing tabata workout:

-Muscle Snatch- 205 lbs / 93 kg
-Deadlift (snatch grip)- 405 lbs / 184 kg 
-High Pull (snatch grip)- 165 lbs / 75 kg
-Klokov Press- 205 lbs / 93 kg
-GHD Back Extension- w/ 95lbs / 45 kg
-Deficit Strict Handstand Push-ups- bodyweight
-Thrusters- 315 lbs / 143 kg
-Jumping Back Squat- 115 lbs / 52 kg

Dmitry also takes a moment to talk about his own history, weightlifting, and CrossFit. 

Dmitry Klokov:
-Olympic Games Silver Medal 2008
-World Champion 2005
-European champion 2010 

Dmitry Klokov YouTube channel: 
https://www.youtube.com/44252005

TABATA SONGS. "Let the Music be your Coach"
 http://www.TabataSongs.com

Filmed at Santa Cruz Strength in Santa Cruz, CA
http://www.santacruzstrength.com/

Filmed by David Leys
http://www.storylightproductions.com/

Tabata Songs creates music that matches the exact timing of the Tabata Protocol. 

What is the Tabata Protocol? Twenty seconds of sprint/work, ten second rest, for four straight minutes. Tabata music lets you focus on your workout, rather than think about having to look at your watch or a timer.

Tabata Training began in the mid 1990's. Japanese fitness researcher Dr Izumi Tabata created a HIIT (high intensity interval training) workout, using this very method. Dr Tabata proved the tabata method to draw heavily from both the aerobic and anaerobic systems, unlike most conventional workouts, which tend heavily favor one or the other. 

The Tabata Interval has gained a lot of recognition throughout the Crossfit community, running community, and health clubs across the globe, for its versatility, adaptability, and positive results. 

The Tabata Interval Method has proven to maximize VO2 max, while also building endurance, burning fat, and retaining muscle. Though the Tabata was not designed as a fat loss or weight loss program, it has gained a lot of recent attention in response to tabatas ability to speed up the metabolism and burn fat.'

Title: b'How to Do Medicine Ball Exercises | Gym Workout'
Description:
b"Like these Gym Workouts !!! Check out the official app http://apple.co/215Vj7h

Watch more How to Work Out at the Gym videos: http://www.howcast.com/videos/503979-How-to-Do-Medicine-Ball-Exercises-Gym-Workout



Hi guys. This is Max Tapper again for Howcast. And what we are going to do today is go over a couple of medicine ball exercises. I know that you guys have seen this everywhere. This is a medicine ball. This is about ten pounds and you can use this to add weight to any different exercise you want. We're going to choose a few today and go through them and let you see how it looks. Okay?

So the first one we're going to use is a Torso Twist with the medicine ball, which is a core exercise that targets every single muscle in here and your lower back. Alright? So take a look. We start off with our feet off the floor going across. One. That's one medicine ball exercise. 

The second one we're going to do is another abs exercise where we're going to use this medicine ball to make our upper body heavier. Alright? So take a look. We're going to lie back on this pad, hold this over our head and we're just going to bring this up to the ceiling. Also another excellent exercise for your abdominals. 

Now, the third exercise is going to be a body squat with the medicine ball. Alright? So follow me, let me show you how this works. The way we're going to start is use this medicine ball in our squat. Then as we're coming up we're going to lift it into a bicep curl, press over the top of the head, bring it back down to the chest, let it back down, squat with this weight. As we're coming up, bicep curl with it, over the head. This is what it'll look like at regular speed. Boom! 

That was a body squat with a medicine ball.

Alright guys. So you can see that was a body squat with a medicine ball added to weight to my workout. Now you can use any different medicine ball that you want. These go up to maybe 30, 40 pounds. Grab any one that you're most comfortable with and do it. You can use these for almost every single exercise. You can do lunges with this. No matter what it is you can find a way to integrate a medicine ball into your workout. Alright?

So guys, spin things around. Go get a medicine ball, add a new workout, have a good time and be safe."

Title: b'Belt Squats using a Hip Squats Belt'
Description:
b"More Exercises For a Bigger Butt @ https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PL81340FB9498C55DF & More Exercises for Thicker Thighs @ https://www.youtube.com/playlist?action_edit=1&list=PL5qWKDYV54nHcAcUGMT64-B1NFONT2Tle

You can get a hips squats belt from nowloss.com/belt
Hip belt squats are a favorite of mine since I'm basically scared to do squats since I never have anyone spot me at the gym but the reason why they may be the best way to squat is because your lower back is taken entirely out of the movement and your legs (butt, hips and thighs) have to do all the work so if you're used to squatting 400 pounds in the barbell squat...

Do not automatically assume you can belt squat 400 pounds. As a matter of fact you probably want to start off with 60% of your max to be safe just get an idea of how much you can do because in barbell squats your lower back and upper body muscles also contribute in some part of helping you complete the lift.

I usually advocate a lower rep range for increased muscle mass but I've gotten results using a high and low rep scheme on belt squats and I do this because I need to start off with high reps as a kind of a warm-up for my knees so my workout usual goes like this and the results are awesome...

Set 1= 20 reps
Set 2 = 18 reps
Set 3 = 15 reps
Set 4 =12 reps
Sets 5, 6 & 7 = 10 reps
Set 8 = 20-to-30 reps

It's a brutal workout.

I usually tie the belt or the carabineer to the lowest loop on the bar so I can get a full range of motion for my butt, hips and thighs and if you have trouble getting a deeper range of motion then you need to stretch your calves, and hip flexors in order to get deeper but you'll see that as you get stronger in the belt squat you'll be able to squat deeper. lower body stretches: http://www.nowloss.com/how-to-stretch-warm-up.htm#butt-hip-thighs-hamstring-calf-stretches

Title: b'Six Pack Abs By Working Your Legs? (get ripped secret revealed)'
Description:
b'http://joecarabase.com

What are the best exercises for six pack abs? sit ups, crunches, the ab coaster? 

None of the above....and defiantly not the ab coaster! Although my mom does own that dumb thing. I digress...

Today I'm talking about the Front Squat baby.

The front squat is one of the most difficult exercises to perform, which is a good thing. This means there is a ton of different muscle involvement and energy used to perform the movement. This will translate into a greater fat burn post workout.

Additionally, you simply can not front squat without activating your core. You have to use your core to perform the movement. Take for example the plank or the pillar, just by virtue of getting into the position does not mean you are activating your core. In fact, most people do not in those movements...

Take aways for you:
1. Perform difficult exercises
2. Add the front squat to your routine
3. Do not just focus on your abs. Instead focus on full body or multi joint movements that require a lot of energy. And let's not forget about nutrition :)

Title: b'Workout 2 Times Per Day? (Good or Bad)'
Description:
b"Working Out Twice Per Day - Should You Do It?

Free Workout Program: http://www.leehayward.com/youtube
Join the Inner Circle: http://www.totalfitnessbodybuilding.com
Facebook: https://www.facebook.com/total.fitness.bodybuilding

What are the benefits of working out twice per day? Will 2 workouts per day lead to better muscle gains, or will it just cause you to over train faster? Is there a time when you should train 2 times per day and a time when you should only workout once per day?

That's what we're going to cover in this video...

The main advantage to working out 2 times per day is that you'll burn more calories and elevate your metabolism more, thus you'll burn bodyfat faster.

When I'm training for fat loss or dieting for a bodybuilding competition I'll purposely do 2 workouts per day. Generally a cardio workout in the morning and a weight training workout in the evening. This will spike your metabolism twice per day and burn more total calories and more bodyfat than if you just worked out once per day. It's much easier to get into a caloric deficit for fat loss when working out twice per day.

Now on the flip side, when I'm training for mass building or bulking up, I prefer to workout once per day. And I'll even drop back to working out every second day. I have found from my own training and with coaching others that most people will make faster size and strength gains when giving their body a full 48 hours of rest in between workouts. Reducing the frequency of your workouts also conserves calories and makes it easier to get into a caloric surplus for bulking.

So the general guideline... For fat loss workout 2 times per day. And for mass building workout 1 time per day, or even every second day.

If you have any questions or comments about this video, please post them in the comments section below and I'll chat with you there."

Los niveles intermedios; deber\xc3\xadan hacer entrenamiento, de cuerpo completo; pero eventualmente, pueden dividir; su entrenamiento, a 4 o 6 d\xc3\xadas; por semana, o pueden combinar; fases de entrenamiento, de cuerpo completo; alternando d\xc3\xadas, de entrenamiento; para distintas, partes del cuerpo. Por ejemplo, los gimnastas, y levantadores ol\xc3\xadmpicos; son de los m\xc3\xa1s fuertes, y m\xc3\xa1s grandes; porque ellos entrenan, su cuerpo completo; de  6 a 7 d\xc3\xadas, a la semana. Realmente, depende de cada qui\xc3\xa9n; y lo que hacen, en sus entrenamientos. Yo dir\xc3\xada, que cuatro veces por semana; de cuerpo dividido, es suficiente; para ganar masa muscular.
\xc2\xbfCu\xc3\xa1ntos D\xc3\xadas, a La Semana; Debo Entrenar, Cada Parte; Del Cuerpo?.
Cargar m\xc3\xa1s peso, y m\xc3\xa1s frecuencia; son los factores, m\xc3\xa1s importantes, para desarrollar m\xc3\xbasculo. Entre m\xc3\xa1s, entrenes un m\xc3\xbasculo, estimulando su fuerza; sin exceder, su capacidad, para recuperarse; m\xc3\xa1s grande, se volver\xc3\xa1. Los principiantes, deben entrenar; cada grupo muscular, un m\xc3\xadnimo de 3 veces; por semana. Cuando eres d\xc3\xa9bil; y empiezas, a aprender; levantamientos de pesas, necesitas exponerte; m\xc3\xa1s frecuentemente. de 5 o 6 sesiones, de 30 minutos; por semana, son muy buenas; pero si s\xc3\xb3lo, puedes hacer 3; est\xc3\xa1 bien.
Los que ya pasaron, el nivel de principiantes; deben entrenar, cada grupo; muscular del cuerpo, al menos dos veces; por semana, o mejor, de 5 o 6. (Las personas avanzadas, con gran habilidad; para recuperarse, y tiempo suficiente; para dedicarse al entrenamiento). Eso te da, m\xc3\xa1s oportunidad; de estimular el crecimiento muscular, en lugar de entrenar; cada grupo, s\xc3\xb3lo una vez; por semana. Quien quiere, mejorar en lo que sea, en su vida; lo hace m\xc3\xa1s frecuente, no menos. La constancia, es la clave del \xc3\xa9xito. Entrena; lo m\xc3\xa1s frecuente, que puedas; sin afectar tu habilidad, para recuperarte. Para la mayor\xc3\xada; de la gente, esto es 3 veces; por semana.'

Title: b'Ankle Warm Up Series. Free Online Foot Fitness Video'
Description:
b"http://carolinejordanfitness.com/

Plantar fasciitis ? Achielles tendonitus? Foot pain? NOT if you have a regular foot and ankle workout program! Take care of your feet and work foot and ankle specific stretching and strengthening into your weekly fitness regimen. In this 4 minute video, fitness professional Caroline Jordan leads you through a quick fitness warm up for your ankles and feet. This free routine does not require any equipment and can be done anywhere.  Foot and ankle stretches improve the joints' mobility and prevent stiffness that can inhibit your ability to move. Stretches also help prevent knee and shin pain and plantar fasciitis when you run, cycle, walk, or exercise. When you stretch your feet, its always good to incorporate your legs and hips in some of the stretches.

Aim to do these exercises multiple times a week, before or after your workout or at home. Do you strengthen and stretch your feet, ankles, and toes? Leave me a comment below and tell me when you have tried the foot workout and if it helps you build strong feet :)

Title: b'20 Min Toning Chest Workout Routine'
Description:
b"http://www.cecilebayeul.com - 20 Min Toning Chest Workout Routine

- Cable Crossover
- Dumbbell Press
- Dumbbell Flys
- Decline Dumbbell Press
- Incline Bench Press

If you do 1 set each of 8 to 15 reps, this will take you around 7 minutes. If you do 2 sets  each of 8 to 15 reps with a 40-60 sec rest in between sets, then this routine will take you around 15 minutes. With 3 sets  each of 8 to 15 reps then this will last around 20 to 25 min. I do 3 sets  each of 8 to 15 reps with a 10-20 sec rest in between sets but if you are just starting out, 1 set each is more than enough ! :)

Make sure to use light weights to be able to perform slower motion to put more tension on the muscle and focus more on the contraction. That allows your brain to understand the movement and really use the chest muscle.

That's it for today. I hope that you enjoyed this video. If you did be sure to click LIKE and share it with your friends on Facebook, Twitter and/or Google Plus. Also be sure to visit my website at :

for free training and nutrition information.

Title: b"Bodybuilders vs. CrossFitters: Who's More Fit? | You Asked For It"
Description:
b'Bodybuilders vs. CrossFitters: Who's More Fit? | You Asked For It; In this episode of You Asked For It, Host, Melana Scantlin from "The World Series of Blackjack" checks in with Expert Trainers & Bodybuilders, James Ellis & Courtney Prather, and CrossFit Coaches and Fitness Pros, Madeline Mosier & Nick Phillips to get some of your fitness questions answered regarding the very subjective topic of which form of training will get you to the highest level of fitness, bodybuilding or CrossFit, and what the experts believe each method has to offer.  First, the bodybuilders explain the difference in intensity between the two forms, what bodybuilding means to them, and that while they often times look more in shape, they actually consider the CrossFitters to be more fit in some ways where endurance, functionality, and work capacity are concerned. Next the panel discusses examples of marathon runners versus power lifters, and weighs in on the fact that CrossFit training is widely used in law enforcement as well as the military. Finally, the CrossFit Experts explain the unique combination of training styles that comprise the form such as functional training, strength training, high intensity cardio training, power lifting intervals, and even some gymnastics moves, and why they believe it offers such drastic results. Find out why everyone has their own idea of "fit" and which one may work best in order to achieve your personal fitness goals. Be sure to tune in to the BeFit Channel every week for more new episodes featuring health, nutrition, and fitness advice from our panel of experts. Don't forget that you might get your questions answered too, by posting them in the comments below the weekly "You Asked For It" videos. Title: b"Day 4. Lower Body Workout (Joe Defranco's WSFSB Variation)"
Description:
b"In this video I am working through Day 4 of Joe Defranco's WSFSB Variation Strength Training Program. Here are my thoughts on the workout:

Box Squats -- Great functional exercise!  We do this everyday, when sitting down and getting up.  It's a huge calorie burner working the major muscles in the legs and core.  When using heavy weights, your heart rate will soon go up, therefore giving your heart a workout, without having to hit the treadmill.  In the video I paused at rep 4 but then I carried on.  It's not a problem, just carry on.  We all have our limits, as long as you're pushing yourself to the max and doing it with correct technique, don't let that slight pause stop you from carrying on.

Bulgarian split squat -- Great for working on your balance and stabilising muscles.  Working the body in a unilateral movement helps to identify the strengths and weaknesses in your body and what muscle needs strengthening and what needs stretching.  Very rarely are we symmetrical and so it is just as important that attention is needed to work each side of your body individually as well as simultaneously.

45-degree hyperextensions -- Quite often people suffer from lower back pain.  This is often due to poor posture, sedentary lifestyle and weak core.  Many of my clients who initially come to me with back complaints are those sitting in the office all day with very little movement.  This is a great back strengthening exercise that specifically works the lower back.  I would totally recommend this.  If you are a total beginner with a very weak core, regress this exercise to just the prone cobra (on the floor with your arms by your side, whilst activating your glutes keep your feet down and lift your chest off the floor and repeat).

Ground-based, high rep abdominal circuit -- Combo of sprinter sit-ups, V-ups, toe touches, hip thrusts.  This combo is great for the abs and you can certainly feel the burn after each set.  Great circuit that can be done anywhere, no equipment needed therefore no excuses for not working out!!

Overall a great workout!  I really like all of Joe Defranco's workouts as they are all with functional exercises.  Not doing just exercises on the superficial muscles to looking good."

Title: b'How to Build BIG Calves'
Description:
b'Question from Luke via the Facebook page:

"Hi dan, I've made a home gym like yourself and I was wondering if you can demonstrate how I can get big calves like yourself with limited equipment? Exercises?High or Low reps? Cheers"

Ok so many of you are often dropping compliments on my calves, particularly the size of them. As mentioned in the video they are not THAT big, more so it's because I am on dat dere hobbit status.

The calves main roles are ankle plantar flexion ie: raising your heel off the floor. It also does a small job of knee flexion although the hamstrings are the big boys in that department. So you want to concentrate on exercises that require you to raise your heel / flex the calves. 

A few obvious ones are seated and standing calf raises, donkey calf raises... but weightlifting moves like the snatch and clean also do this - it is that ankle flexion that is partly responsible for that massive speed of the second pull.

Remember, like all muscles, genetics plays a huge role. Insertions, muscle bellys etc are going to make a massive difference to the shape and size of a muscle.... but alongside that... if you don't actually train them enough you won't see much from them anyway!

How many people do you know that do 5 different types of bicep curls for a million sets of a billion reps? Yet they train their calves once a week, for 2-3 sets.... Food for thought.

Thanks for watching!

Title: b'GYM MOTIVATION - AMAZING BODY TRANSFORMATION - 15-17 YEARS OLD'
Description:
b"2 years of hard work, eating healthy, lifting, and exercising, currently at 17 years old. (17 1/2)

I (Ryan) used to be an avid RuneScape player, playing on average 5-7+ hours a day, drinking soda, eating chips. I was a skinny guy. I got introduced to parkour, which began to change my life. I started getting interested in eating healthier, and soon weight lifting (to help with parkour). Soon, parkour became too stressful (the time of practice, and my interest leaning toward just lifting), so I decided to just focus on bodybuilding/exercise. 

It's definitely changed my life. I feel SO much better, mentally, psychically, and emotionally, my skin has gotten better (used to have a looot of pimples - still have some problems due to genetics), and my confidence and happiness has definitely been boosted majorly. I'm in total control of my body and how it works. 

Austin has been doing sports throughout school (football, track, cross country) and has always been a skinny guy. However, from parkour & motivating each other, he's just leaned toward bodybuilding as well, and now eats properly as well. We work out 4-5 days a week together.

Title: b'Hip Flexor Release: The 2 Minute Fix'
Description:
b'Here is a link (affiliate) to the bands I recommend: http://amzn.to/1GgBrYh
Get the full protocol for hip mobility from http://program.fullbodyfix.com 
In this video I demonstrate both a standard hip flexor stretch and a banded technique to decompress the spine while mobilizing the muscle. Find the whole post at http://drscottamills.com/2014/11/the-2-minute-fix-hip-flexor-release/

The Problem:
The hip flexors are a group of muscles (iliacus, psoas & rectus femoris) whose primary action is raising the leg. However, one often overlooked action of the psoas is lumbar compression/stabilization. Thus, in order to fully stretch or release the hip flexors, we need to decompress and elongate the lower spine.

The Fix:
I demonstrate the couch stretch, which will help some people. But I spend more time showing a banded technique to open up and release the muscle that may prove more helpful for others.'

Title: b'Selecci\xc3\xb3n nacional juvenil de levantamiento de pesas quiere hacer historia'
Description:
b'Trabajan en serio. La selecci\xc3\xb3n juvenil de levantamiento de pesas, se viene preparando a conciencia trabajando en doble horario, para llegar en \xc3\xb3ptimas condiciones al Campeonato Mundial Junior que se desarrollar\xc3\xa1 en las instalaciones del Hotel Mar\xc3\xada Angola (Miraflores) del 4 al 10 de mayo. Bajo la atenta mirada del t\xc3\xa9cnico b\xc3\xbalgaro Gancho Mitev Karouchkov, los pesistas nacionales van dando forma a su sue\xc3\xb1o de obtener la mayor cantidad de medallas de oro en esta competici\xc3\xb3n.

Son en total 20 lo j\xc3\xb3venes deportistas seleccionados cuyas edades est\xc3\xa1n comprendidas entre los 15 y 20 a\xc3\xb1os. Nueve son damas y once varones. El equipo femenino est\xc3\xa1 compuesto por la loretana Tessy Pizango, la misma que en el reciente Campeonato Mundial Sub 17 de Uzbekist\xc3\xa1n, logr\xc3\xb3 ubicarse entre las 10 mejores de la categor\xc3\xada 58 kg. Ella es especialista en la modalidad de envi\xc3\xb3n.

A Tessy se suman Beatriz Limas, Fiorella Cueva, Cindy Curi, Nadia Vela, Angie C\xc3\xa1rdenas, y Yomara Cajas. En calidad de reservas estar\xc3\xa1n Gloria Urbina y Silvana Saldarriaga. En varones destacan Marcos Rojas, que competir\xc3\xa1 en 56 kilos especialidad de envi\xc3\xb3n. \xc3\x89l recibi\xc3\xb3 hace una semana el Colibr\xc3\xad de Plata por su gran actuaci\xc3\xb3n . Tambi\xc3\xa9n est\xc3\xa1 el piurano Hern\xc3\xa1n Viera, que en los pasados Juegos Panamericanos de Guadalajara (M\xc3\xa9xico) rompi\xc3\xb3 6 records nacionales. Hern\xc3\xa1n, quien viene recuper\xc3\xa1ndose de una lesi\xc3\xb3n; tomar\xc3\xa1 parte en la categor\xc3\xada 94 kilos, siendo su especialidad tanto el arranque como el envi\xc3\xb3n .

Tambi\xc3\xa9n est\xc3\xa1n Miguel Preciado, Joanmanuel Feijoo, Erick C\xc3\xb3rdova, David Bardalez, y \xc3\x93scar Terrones. Junior Alburqueque, Robinson Aquino, y Hugo Saldarriaga van como reservas.

Entre los pa\xc3\xadses que tomar\xc3\xa1n parte del Mundial, destacan n\xc3\xadtidamente Alemania, Kazajist\xc3\xa1n, Colombia, Israel, Italia, y Armenia. El favoritismo lo tiene China, que tiene a Ji Feiyon, reciente ganador de la presea de oro en la modalidad de arranque en el Mundial Sub 17 de Uzbekist\xc3\xa1n.'

La mayor\xc3\xada de los programas de terapia f\xc3\xadsica que est\xc3\xa1n dise\xc3\xb1adas para tratar el dolor de espalda baja y un poco de dolor radicular (dolor que se irradia hacia la pierna) incluir\xc3\xa1 una combinaci\xc3\xb3n de los siguientes tipos de ejercicio:

El estiramiento . El estiramiento adecuado de los m\xc3\xbasculos junto con el ejercicio activo ayudar\xc3\xa1 a mantener el rango normal de movimiento y proporcionar un alivio para los m\xc3\xbasculos que a menudo sufren atrofia por desuso (reducci\xc3\xb3n de los m\xc3\xbasculos por falta de uso) o en el espasmo de la postura inadecuada o irritaci\xc3\xb3n de los nervios. Para muchos pacientes que lo mejor es seguir una rutina de estiramiento que se ha dise\xc3\xb1ado de forma individual para ellos por un fisioterapeuta o un m\xc3\xa9dico columna vertebral. Como regla general, los pacientes con dolor lumbar deben centrarse en el estiramiento de los m\xc3\xbasculos de la espalda baja, los m\xc3\xbasculos abdominales, caderas y piernas. El paciente nunca debe rebotar durante el estiramiento, y todos los tramos debe ser lenta y gradual.

Ver estiramiento para Back Pain Relief
Ejercicios de estabilizaci\xc3\xb3n din\xc3\xa1mica . Estos ejercicios implican el uso de una variedad de ejercicios y pueden incluir el uso de pelotas de ejercicio, m\xc3\xa1quinas de equilibrado o ejercicios de estabilizaci\xc3\xb3n espec\xc3\xadficos. El punto de ejercicios de estabilizaci\xc3\xb3n din\xc3\xa1mica es fortalecer los m\xc3\xbasculos secundarios de la columna vertebral y ayudar a mantener la columna vertebral a trav\xc3\xa9s de diferentes rangos de movimiento.

Fisioterapia Activo - Ejercicios dolor de espalda

Adem\xc3\xa1s de terapias pasivas, terapia f\xc3\xadsica activa (ejercicio) tambi\xc3\xa9n es necesario para la rehabilitaci\xc3\xb3n de la columna vertebral. Generalmente, el programa de ejercicio para la espalda de un paciente debe abarcar una combinaci\xc3\xb3n de los siguientes:

Se extiende por ejercicios de dolor de espalda
casi todas las personas que ha sufrido de dolor de espalda baja debe estirar sus m\xc3\xbasculos isquiotibiales, una o dos veces al d\xc3\xada. Isquiotibiales simple estiramiento no toma mucho tiempo, aunque puede ser dif\xc3\xadcil de recordar, especialmente si hay poco o nada de dolor. Por lo tanto, los ejercicios de estiramiento de los m\xc3\xbasculos isquiotibiales se hacen mejor a la misma hora todos los d\xc3\xadas por lo que se convierte en parte de la rutina diaria de una persona. Hay muchos m\xc3\xa1s tramos que se pueden hacer para aliviar el dolor de espalda baja.
Fortalecimiento para el ejercicio dolor de espalda
Para fortalecer los m\xc3\xbasculos de la espalda, de 15 a 20 minutos de estabilizaci\xc3\xb3n lumbar din\xc3\xa1mica u otros ejercicios prescritos deben realizarse cada dos d\xc3\xadas. Fortalecimiento muscular subyacente tambi\xc3\xa9n es importante en el tratamiento del dolor de espalda baja. Es importante realizar los ejercicios correctamente con el fin de ver los beneficios, por lo que se aprende mejor con la ayuda de un fisioterapeuta u otro profesional de la salud competente. F\xc3\xbcr einen richtig breiten R\xc3\xbccken musst Du etwas mehr tun als nur Rudern oder Lat-Ziehen ... es ist an der Zeit den K\xc3\xb6nig unter den R\xc3\xbccken-\xc3\x9cbungen kennen zu lernen: Den Klimmzug. 

Der Klimmzug ist eine schwere \xc3\x9cbung, die viel Kraft erfordert und dadurch auch den Aufbau von Muskelmasse stimuliert. Daher ist sie auch beim Bodybuilding so popul\xc3\xa4r. Beim Klimmzug gibt es aber viele verschiedene M\xc3\xb6glichkeiten ihn auszuf\xc3\xbchren. Jede Ausf\xc3\xbchrungsweise belastet den R\xc3\xbccken auf eine andere Weise und sorgt so in den entsprechenden Muskelpartien f\xc3\xbcr Wachstum. So bekommst Du nach und nach sowohl einen breiten als auch tiefen R\xc3\xbccken.

Breite Variante:

Du greifst die Stange so, dass sich ein sch\xc3\xb6nes V ergibt, wenn Du ganz unten bist. Bei dieser \xc3\x9cbung wird die hintere Schulter und der \xc3\xa4u\xc3\x9fere R\xc3\xbcckenmuskel trainiert. Durch regelm\xc3\xa4\xc3\x9figes Training bekommst Du damit die sch\xc3\xb6ne V-Form.

Enge Variante:

Je enger Du die Stange greifst, desto mehr werden die tieferen R\xc3\xbcckenmuskeln belastet. Diese sind f\xc3\xbcr die Muskelmasse verantwortlich - damit dein Oberk\xc3\xb6rper massig ausschaut.

Paralleler Griff:

Bei dieser Variante wird der Oberarm, genauer der Brachialis und der Bizeps st\xc3\xa4rker mit trainiert. Wiederum stimulierst Du damit das Muskelwachstum in den tieferen Muskelpartien deines R\xc3\xbcckens.

Enger Griff mit umgedrehten H\xc3\xa4nden.

Diese Ausf\xc3\xbchrungsweise bezieht den Bizeps relativ stark in die \xc3\x9cbung mit ein. Du trainierst damit zur H\xc3\xa4lfte deinen Oberarm und zur H\xc3\xa4lfte deinen R\xc3\xbccken.

Und f\xc3\xbcr all diejenigen unter euch, denen diese Klimmz\xc3\xbcge immer noch zu langweilig sind, habe ich am Schluss eine richtig intensive Variante auf Lager :)

Die verschiedenen Klimmzug-Variationen sind die Voraussetzung f\xc3\xbcr einen tiefen und breiteren R\xc3\xbccken. Nicht ohne Grund schw\xc3\xb6ren alle professionellen Bodybuilder auf diese Muskelaufbau-\xc3\x9cbung. Zu einem muskul\xc3\xb6sen Oberk\xc3\xb6rper geh\xc3\xb6rt aber neben einem massiven R\xc3\xbccken auch eine gro\xc3\x9fe Brust und breite Schultern. Title: b'How to Perform Mountain Climbers'
Description:
b"Ready for another Angry Trainer Fitness video everyone?

We've run a couple of workout programs in a row now so this week we're taking a break from the circuits to talk about one of my favorite exercises that you should ALL be using at part of your regimes...

Few exercises when performed properly provide the same benefits as Mountain Climbers. They work your upper body, especially the shoulders, core and abs, plus a bit of your legs - and your overall endurance. The problem is that most people use horrible form and look more like they're bouncing up a mountain, than climbing it. Yeah - you know who you are!

The Mountain Climber is nothing more than a hand plank in which you rapidly alternate and pull your knees forward. So as a rule, if you can't hold a great plank for 30 seconds, you're not ready for the mountain!

In this video I'm going to show you the WRONG way to perform Mountain Climbers -- and then the RIGHT way. With some simple cuing and direction, you'll be in perfect form in no time. So what are you waiting for...!

By the way -- don't forget to check out my other exercise videos on the Angry Trainer Fitness YouTube Channel!. And if you haven't already become a subscriber...

Alfonso."

Title: b'How To Fix Anterior Pelvic Tilt DEADLIFT'
Description:
b'Fix Anterior Pelvic Tilt Program: https://www.anteriortilt.com
**FREE Copy Of  The Strong Side: 3 ways to improve strength training
http://www.strengthside.com/the-stron...

Anterior Pelvic Tilt can bring many problems in strength training. The problem is that when the Pelvis is tilted forward you can not properly load your hips, meaning develop force from your glutes, hamstrings, and other posterior muscles. This is a big problem in the deadlift because the deadlift is meant to load the hips and use maximal hip drive to complete the lift or movement. In this video we address gaining a better hip position. Topics covered:
Hip, head, and chest awareness
Bracing - butt tight, abs tight, rib cage down, deep breath
Top Down Approach - Hinge style
Bottom Up Approach - Squat to bar style
These are all cues and concepts that the individual can use to get proper mechanics and force production during the deadlift.

Title: b'Great Exercises for Your Abs - Quick Abs Blast'
Description:
b"Save hundreds with Learn Pilates! http://mhlo.co/qvbwyH
In this video,\xc2\xa0Mahalo's fitness\xc2\xa0expert Torri Shack shows you how to work out your abs with this quick abs blast.

Getting Started
---------------------------------------------------------------------

You can do this exercise either at the gym or at home. If you prefer to do them at home, you may be more comfortable performing this exercise on a yoga mat, towel or any other soft surface you can put between you and the floor.c\xc2\xa0

Muscles Worked
---------------------------------------------------------------------

This exercise works your rectus abdominis muscles, which are the major muscle group in your core and the muscles responsible for the six-pack look.c\xc2\xa0

Start this exercise by lying flat on you back with your legs outstretch along the floor and both hands under your hips/butt for support. From this position, try one of these variations:

* Raise your legs so that they are perpendicular to the ground. Lower them towards the ground without actually touching. Raise them back to the starting position.
* If you have lower back problems, instead of having your legs straight in the air, bend them at your knees and then extend so they are parallel to the floor. Bend back to the starting position.
* To make the move harder, start with you legs at a 45
\xc2\xb0 angle to the floor and lower them so they hover above the ground. Keep raising and lowering them at that half-way point.* Bring your knees above your hips so your shins are parallel to the ground. Crunch up and tap your heels. Lower back to start.
* Instead of having your hands under your hips, place them out to the side so they are in line with your chest. Bring your knees to your chest as you crunch upward. Tap your heels, then stretch your legs so they hover above the ground to complete one rep.

For each of these exercises, try to complete three sets of 15-20 reps.

Read more by visiting our page at:
http://www.mahalo.com/quick-abs-blast/"

Title: b'Muay Thai Test Session'
Description:
b'I used to be a student and assistant instructor at the Muay Thai Academy International in San Jose, CA. I stopped going about 10 years ago (primarily due to chronic injuries). Today I decided to try practicing my Muay Thai (Thai boxing) techniques to see how they're holding up.

Location: Muay Thai Academy International
Me: 6' 1", 157 lbs, age 50
Heavy bag: 170-180 lb overstuffed "banana" bag

UPDATE: That bag was harder than the ones I used to use most frequently, and my shins and knees felt a little tender from bruising for about two weeks after this workout. But the muscle down the outside of my left shin took four weeks to no longer feel bruised (not surprising--I've always had imperfect form with my left shin kick, which can cause the muscle to take a beating).'

Title: b'I, BODYBUILDER - Shoulders 1'
Description:
b"I,BODYBUILDER Program Overview

The I,BODYBUILDER Program is divided into 5 phases, 4 are body-part specific, and the fifth is a transition program:

PHASE 1 - Shoulders
PHASE 2 - Back
PHASE 3 - Legs
PHASE 4 - Chest
PHASE 5 - Transition

Depending upon your progress, and the areas of weaknesses you need to work on, each phase can last between 2 and 4 weeks. But it's totally up to you when to move on to the next phase.

Regardless of the areas you want to focus on, please follow the order of the phases. In other words, don't skip a phase just because you don't think you need to work on, let's say, shoulders for example. Or don't change the order of the phases to meet your specific priorities.

The reason being, each phase is designed to build on the previous phase. And the overall design is based on providing the very best gains for all problem areas, including arms (which don't have their own phase).

We chose a body-part specialization approach because, if utilized in a comprehensive program, it's one of the most-effective ways to make the largest overall gains. In other words, emphasizing one major body part at a time \xe2\x80\x94 without neglecting the rest of the body \xe2\x80\x94 will lead to the greatest overall gains by the end of 12 weeks.

We know we've said this so many times, but the program works. We know it because we've tested it.

Anyway, just do what we ask, please, and don't screw up the order. And we mean this in the nicest way. Really.

http://www.t-nation.com/free_online_program/sports_body_training_muscle_anaconda/anaconda_protocol#1-8211-guidelines"
